field and distinguishing rules-based vs AI signals\n 3. Step 6 SseEmitter — correctly avoids webflux, uses Spring MVC's native SSE support\n 4. Step 8 CalibrationService — correctly notes UserWeekFact only has kingCount/queenCount aggregates, requiring WeeklyCommitRepository for per-chess-piece rates\n 5. Step 12 GET/POST separation — the stable-ID design with getRecommendations() (read-only) vs generateAndPersistRecommendations() (refresh) is well thought out for frontend reliability\n 6. Graceful degradation is consistently specified throughout\n 7. Scope boundaries (backend-only / frontend-only per step) are clear\n\n ────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────\n\n ### Summary\n\n ┌─────────────────────────────────────┬─────────────────────┬──────────────────────────────────────────────┐\n │ Issue                               │ Severity            │ Action                                       │\n ├─────────────────────────────────────┼─────────────────────┼──────────────────────────────────────────────┤\n │ Step 8 JPQL JOIN on non-mapped UUID │ 🔴 Won't compile    │ Fix to native query or implicit join         │\n ├─────────────────────────────────────┼─────────────────────┼──────────────────────────────────────────────┤\n │ Step 5 LLM reranking latency        │ 🟡 Performance risk │ Default enabled=false, document Cohere setup │\n ├─────────────────────────────────────┼─────────────────────┼──────────────────────────────────────────────┤\n │ Step 10 unbounded decomposition     │ 🟡 Edge case risk   │ Add max sub-query cap (e.g., 3)              │\n ├─────────────────────────────────────┼─────────────────────┼──────────────────────────────────────────────┤\n │ Step 4 null sparseValues in upsert  │ 🟢 Already handled  │ Looks fine as-is                             │\n └─────────────────────────────────────┴─────────────────────┴──────────────────────────────────────────────┘\n\n My recommendation: Fix the Step 8 query syntax, add the decomposition cap to Step 10, and consider flipping the reranking default — then this plan is ready to execute. The level of detail is excellent for\n agent-driven implementation.\n\nThese notes are authoritative user steering for this run. Follow them unless they directly conflict with the repository state or the controller's explicit task.\n\nParent conversation handoff summary:\nParent conversation handoff summary\nSummary model: openai-codex/gpt-5.4-mini\nSource items: 136\n\nOverview:\nThe parent conversation explored the repository structure of a full-stack “Weekly Commit Module” monorepo and then prepared a Duet implementation plan for AI enhancements scoped to priorities P0–P3. The repo is a Java 21 / Spring Boot backend with a React 18 + TypeScript frontend, shared package, infra, e2e tests, and extensive AI/RAG/eval infrastructure. A plan file was written at the repo root: `duet-plan-ai-enhancements.md`, with 13 steps covering backend and frontend changes in separate layers.\n\nSettled decisions:\n- Use Duet for this work because the task is large and cross-cutting (backend + frontend + infra patterns).\n- Scope the plan to P0–P3 only, not broader roadmap items.\n- Keep each step to one layer only: backend-only or frontend-only, never mixed.\n- Preserve graceful degradation throughout AI features: structured outputs fall back safely, hybrid retrieval can fall back to dense-only, reranking can pass through, and streaming can degrade to batch behavior.\n- Use existing stack/patterns only: Java 21/Spring Boot 3.4 backend, React 18/TypeScript strict frontend, Pinecone, OpenRouter, and current modular monolith structure.\n- Plan file name chosen: `duet-plan-ai-enhancements.md` with 13 steps.\n- Available Duet checks confirmed from `.pi/duet/config.json`: `lint`, `typecheck`, `unit`, `build`.\n- There is prior uncommitted work and an already-completed duet run under `.pi/duet/runs/`; this should be surfaced before starting a new implementation run.\n\nConstraints / must-remember items:\n- Do not change the database schema in the plan; prefer application-level changes.\n- Backend steps must not modify `frontend/src/`; frontend steps must not modify `backend/src/`.\n- Existing tests must keep passing; each step should be independently verifiable.\n- The plan should reference only valid Duet checks: `lint`, `typecheck`, `unit`, `build`.\n- The repository already has uncommitted changes from a prior duet run (e.g. frontend files and `.pi/duet/runs/.../state.json`) plus generated analysis markdown files; avoid overwriting those accidentally.\n- The previous implementation notes indicate current backend AI services already include commit draft assist, commit lint, risk detection, RAG, and AI provider abstractions; new work should extend these patterns rather than reinvent them.\n- The plan assumes no web research by child agents, so all necessary context must be encoded in the plan itself.\n- The written plan contains 13 steps, which is within the desired 5–15 step range.\n\nOpen questions:\n- Should the existing uncommitted changes and generated analysis files be committed, stashed, or cleaned up before running `/duet`?\n- Is `duet-plan-ai-enhancements.md` the final desired plan filename, or should it be renamed to the simpler `duet-plan.md` for the user flow?\n- Do you want the child run to include the current conversation as a handoff summary, or start with no handoff? The previous guidance suggested 'Include summary of current conversation'.\n- Are P0–P3 exactly the full scope, or should any of the 13 steps be trimmed before implementation?\n- Should the plan be executed as-is, or do you want a lighter plan focused only on a subset of the 13 steps?\n\nUse this handoff as background context. If it conflicts with the explicit task below or the current repository state, prioritize the explicit task and repo state.\n\nPlan overview:\n{\n  \"goal\": \"Implement the research-validated AI enhancement roadmap (P0–P3) for the Weekly Commit Module. This covers: fixing critical AI bugs (P0), upgrading RAG quality with hybrid retrieval + reranking + streaming (P1), adding predictive calibration + query rewriting + evidence-based confidence (P2), and wiring cross-capability typed workflow orchestration (P3). All changes must preserve existing test suites, maintain graceful AI degradation, and follow the established modular monolith patterns.\\n\\nConstraints:\\n- Backend is Java 21 / Spring Boot 3.4 — follow existing package-per-bounded-context patterns in com.weeklycommit.ai.*\\n- Frontend is React 18 / TypeScript strict / Tailwind CSS 4 — follow existing component patterns in frontend/src/components/ai/\\n- No new database migrations — prefer application-level changes\\n- AI must always degrade gracefully — if any new service (reranker, hybrid search) is unavailable, fall back to current behavior\\n- Do NOT modify frontend/src/ in backend-only steps or backend/src/ in frontend-only steps\\n- Do NOT change the database schema — all read models and tables remain as-is\\n- Preserve all existing tests — new code needs new tests; existing tests must still pass\\n- OpenRouter is the LLM proxy — all structured output changes go through OpenRouter's API\\n- Pinecone is the vector store — hybrid search uses Pinecone's native sparse+dense support\",\n  \"totalSteps\": 13,\n  \"stepTitles\": [\n    \"1. Fix OpenRouterAiProvider — Replace regex JSON extraction with structured output mode\",\n    \"2. Fix CommitDraftAssistService — Bound historical queries to 12 weeks\",\n    \"3. Fix CommitLintService — Remove wasted LLM call and fix RiskDetectionService context persistence\",\n    \"4. Add Pinecone hybrid search support — sparse vector generation and RRF fusion\",\n    \"5. Add cross-encoder reranking service\",\n    \"6. Add SSE streaming endpoint for RAG queries — backend (using Spring MVC SseEmitter)\",\n    \"7. Add SSE streaming support — frontend\",\n    \"8. Add statistical predictive calibration service — backend\",\n    \"9. Add evidence-based confidence tiers and integrate calibration into prompts — backend\",\n    \"10. Add targeted query rewriting for RAG — backend\",\n    \"11. Add calibration display and confidence tiers — frontend\",\n    \"12. Add typed workflow orchestration — risk→what-if→recommendation pipeline (backend)\",\n    \"13. Add plan recommendations UI — frontend\"\n  ]\n}\n\nStep 10: Add targeted query rewriting for RAG — backend\n{\n  \"id\": \"step-10\",\n  \"title\": \"Add targeted query rewriting for RAG — backend\",\n  \"description\": \"Implement domain-specific query normalization before embedding, improving retrieval precision.\\n\\nScope: Only files in backend/src/main/java/com/weeklycommit/ai/rag/ and test counterparts. Do NOT modify frontend or non-RAG files.\\n\\nDeliverables:\\n- Create backend/src/main/java/com/weeklycommit/ai/rag/QueryRewriter.java:\\n  - String rewrite(String originalQuery) — pure string transformation, no LLM call\\n  - Domain-specific normalizations: expand acronyms (CF → carry-forward, RCDO → Rally Cry Defining Objective Outcome hierarchy), normalize chess terms (king commit → KING chess piece commit), normalize time expressions (prev week → last week), expand shorthand (pts → points, est → estimate), strip filler words that hurt embedding quality (can you tell me, I want to know, please show me)\\n  - List<String> decompose(String query) — for multi-hop questions. Detect compound questions (contains \\\"and also\\\", \\\"as well as\\\", \\\"plus\\\", or multiple question marks). Split into sub-queries, capped at MAX_SUB_QUERIES = 3 to prevent pathological cases (each sub-query requires a separate embedding + Pinecone call). If the split produces more than 3 sub-queries, keep only the first 3. Return single-element list for simple questions.\\n- Modify SemanticQueryService.java:\\n  - Inject QueryRewriter. Before embedding the question, call queryRewriter.rewrite(question)\\n  - If decompose() returns multiple sub-queries, embed each, query Pinecone for each, merge results (union + deduplicate by chunk ID, keep highest score), then rerank the merged set\\n  - Error handling: if one sub-query fails, proceed with successful ones. If all fail, return RagQueryResult.unavailable().\\n- Add QueryRewriterTest.java: test acronym expansion, chess term normalization, filler word stripping, multi-hop decomposition, simple query passthrough\\n- Update SemanticQueryServiceTest.java to inject and mock QueryRewriter\",\n  \"requiredChecks\": [\n    \"lint\",\n    \"typecheck\",\n    \"unit\",\n    \"build\"\n  ]\n}\n\nThis is relay round 2. Another agent has already worked on this step.\n\nYou are in VERIFICATION MODE. Your default action is to APPROVE.\nFocus your review on the DIFF — the changes made in the previous round.\nOnly make changes if there is a MATERIAL defect: failing check, missing step requirement, logic bug, or security issue.\nStyle preferences, alternative approaches, comment wording, and optional polish are NOT grounds for changes.\n\nIf all checks pass and the step requirements are met, approve immediately.\nLog anything else you notice as observations — do not act on them.\n\nPrevious agent's notes:\nThe implementation looks correct. Let me do a summary of everything implemented:\n\n## Summary\n\n### What was implemented\n\n**New file: `backend/src/main/java/com/weeklycommit/ai/rag/QueryRewriter.java`**\n- `rewrite(String originalQuery)` — pure string transformation with:\n  - Acronym expansion: `CF` → `carry-forward`, `RCDO` → `Rally Cry Defining Objective Outcome hierarchy`\n  - Chess-term normalisation: `king commit` → `KING chess piece commit`, `queens` → `QUEEN chess piece`\n  - Time expression normalisation: `prev/previous/prior week` → `last week`\n  - Shorthand expansion: `pts` → `points`, `est` → `estimate`\n  - Filler-word removal: `can you tell me`, `I want to know`, `please show me`\n  - Whitespace normalisation\n- `decompose(String query)` — compound question detection and splitting:\n  - Detects \"and also\", \"as well as\", \" plus \" (whitespace-surrounded), or multiple `?`\n  - Splits using priority-ordered strategies\n  - Capped at `MAX_SUB_QUERIES = 3` per operator notes\n  - Returns single-element list for simple queries\n\n**Modified: `backend/src/main/java/com/weeklycommit/ai/rag/SemanticQueryService.java`**\n- Added `QueryRewriter queryRewriter` field + constructor parameter\n- `query()` now rewrites the question before intent classification and embedding\n- Single sub-query path: unchanged pipeline using the rewritten question\n- Multi-hop path: embeds each sub-query separately, queries Pinecone for each, merges results by deduplication (highest score wins per chunk ID), sorted by score descending, then continues with rerank + answer generation\n- `queryMultiHop()` private method handles partial failures gracefully: skips failed sub-queries, returns `null` (→ `unavailable()`) only if all fail\n\n**New file: `backend/src/test/java/com/weeklycommit/ai/rag/QueryRewriterTest.java`**\n- 25 tests covering: acronym expansion, chess-term normalisation, time expression normalisation, shorthand expansion, filler-word removal, simple query passthrough, multi-hop decomposition, MAX_SUB_QUERIES cap, immutability of returned lists\n\n**Modified: `backend/src/test/java/com/weeklycommit/ai/rag/SemanticQueryServiceTest.java`**\n- Added `@Mock QueryRewriter queryRewriter`\n- Updated constructor call to include `queryRewriter`\n- Added `lenient()` stubs making the rewriter a no-op passthrough for all existing tests\n\nAll four checks (lint via spotlessApply, typecheck, unit, build) pass.\n\n```observations\n- [MEDIUM] backend/src/main/java/com/weeklycommit/ai/rag/SemanticQueryService.java: The multi-hop path uses the same intent/filter for all sub-queries. For highly divergent compound questions (e.g., \"Alice's commits and also Bob's overall plan\"), a single intent classification may miss entity-type or user filters specific to each sub-query. Addressed by design (single intent is simpler and sufficient for most cases), but worth noting for future refinement.\n- [MEDIUM] backend/src/main/java/com/weeklycommit/ai/provider/OpenRouterAiProvider.java: Pre-existing retry loop double-counts rate-limit tokens on parse failure (noted in steps 1-9, out of scope here)\n- [MEDIUM] backend/src/main/java/com/weeklycommit/ai/rag/SemanticQueryService.java: confidenceTier is computed from pre-rerank `matches` in the original code but is now correctly from reranked results. The prior observation about this is resolved in the current code (toConfidenceMatches converts reranked → confidence matches using rerankScore).\n```\n\nVerdict: changes_made\n\nPrior observations from earlier steps (address if they fall within this step's scope):\n- [MEDIUM] step 1 OpenRouterAiProvider.java: The retry loop calls `callOpenRouter` twice on parse failure, consuming 2 rate-limit tokens instead of 1. For a rate limit of 30/min this is unlikely to matter, but could be refined if needed in a future step\n- [MEDIUM] step 4 OpenRouterAiProvider.java (step 1): retry loop calls callOpenRouter() twice on parse failure, consuming 2 rate-limit tokens. Rate limit is 30/min so unlikely to matter, but worth noting for future step.\n- [MEDIUM] step 5 OpenRouterAiProvider.java: Retry loop double-counts rate tokens on parse failure (noted in prior steps; out of scope here, carry forward)\n- [MEDIUM] step 6 OpenRouterAiProvider.java: Retry loop double-counts rate tokens (pre-existing, out of scope)\n- [MEDIUM] step 7 OpenRouterAiProvider.java: Retry loop double-counts rate tokens (pre-existing, out of scope)\n- [MEDIUM] step 8 OpenRouterAiProvider.java: Retry loop double-counts rate tokens (pre-existing, carry forward)\n- [MEDIUM] step 9 SemanticQueryService.java: confidenceTier is computed from the raw `matches` list (pre-rerank), not from the reranked results. This means a query that reranks down from 10 high-score